03882nam a22005055i 9780773580749DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20102010xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735807497 a10.1515/97807735807492doi  a(DE-B1597)656925  a(OCoLC)770682484  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aLB14.7.K39 2010eb 7aFOR0300002bisacsh04a370.11 aKazepides, Tasos, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEducation as Dialogue :bIts Prerequisites and its Enemies /cTasos Kazepides. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (218 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tA Clarification of Relevant Educational Concepts -- tPhilosophical Inquiry in Education -- tThe Concept of Education -- tCan Education Have Aims? -- tThe Prerequisites of Education and Dialogue, the Criteria of Indoctrination, and the Educational Dimensions of Human Nature -- tThe Prerequisites of Education -- tEducation as Dialogue -- tForms of Miseducation -- tThe Enemies of Dialogue -- tEducation, Dialogue, and Human Nature -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough talk about dialogue is common, nothing clear, significant, and educationally useful has been written about the nature of dialogue and the principles and conditions that support or undermine it. Education as Dialogue argues that true dialogue and education require beliefs, rules, virtues, and habits that facilitate learning while preventing the acquisition of doctrines. Tasos Kazepides shows that the prerequisites for dialogue and education are similar to Ludwig Wittgenstein's concept of "river-bed propositions" - propositions that are the foundation of our ability to think and to reason. He argues that understanding education as genuine dialogue ought to become central to educational theory and practice because it is the most appropriate and effective way to motivate and engage students and the best way to guard against indoctrination. The pivotal importance of education as dialogue is emphasized for its capacity to encourage critical thought, in contrast to indoctrination, which arrests, limits, or frustrates thought. Taking a unique approach to thinking about education, Kazepides provides a welcome and instructive work that stresses the importance of seeing education as dialogue.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aFOREIGN LANGUAGE STUDY / Indic Languages.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358074940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773580749423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773580749/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  aGBV-deGruyter-alles